WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.280
The slides for my talk are available on my website fharrell.com, so go there, you can

00:00:12.280 --> 00:00:16.840
get the slides and inside the slides you'll see the links to the demonstration reports

00:00:16.840 --> 00:00:20.080
that I'll be showing you parts of in this talk.

00:00:20.080 --> 00:00:24.959
Also if you want to follow somebody on Twitter who likes to criticize poorly done statistics

00:00:24.959 --> 00:00:31.600
or poorly done machine learning, follow F2Harrell on Twitter, I'd be glad to have you there

00:00:31.600 --> 00:00:37.200
discuss those issues and more.

00:00:37.200 --> 00:00:43.119
So just a brief mention of interactive graphics and what sort of levels of interactivity.

00:00:43.119 --> 00:00:48.840
Most of you know this really well, but there's full interactivity using tools such as RShiny

00:00:48.840 --> 00:00:53.639
where you can change your mind about what variables you're analyzing and how you're

00:00:53.639 --> 00:00:58.119
analyzing them such as how much smoothing to do in a non-parametric smoother.

00:00:58.119 --> 00:01:02.360
But what I'm going to be talking about today is partial interactivity.

00:01:02.360 --> 00:01:06.480
So what sort of things can you do with partial interactivity?

00:01:06.480 --> 00:01:13.639
You can zoom and pan, rescale axes, provide extra information using pop-ups such as hover

00:01:13.639 --> 00:01:17.800
text when you hover the mouse over an area.

00:01:17.800 --> 00:01:22.760
And then very importantly is you can select which traces of data that you want to show,

00:01:22.879 --> 00:01:26.800
which elements of a graph do you want to show.

00:01:26.800 --> 00:01:33.239
And then instead of having legends and explanations, I think it's better to have information available

00:01:33.239 --> 00:01:34.239
on demand.

00:01:34.239 --> 00:01:39.639
So instead of devoting space to things to explain what are the elements of a box plot,

00:01:39.639 --> 00:01:44.040
when you hover over that part of a box plot, just have the definition of which quantile

00:01:44.040 --> 00:01:48.400
you're showing pop up for you.

00:01:48.400 --> 00:01:54.720
So I'm using the Plotly package, which I'm a huge fan of, which is using the famous D3

00:01:54.720 --> 00:01:59.680
JavaScript graphics library.

00:01:59.680 --> 00:02:07.720
This in my mind is the best partially interactive scientific graphics system and it has its

00:02:07.720 --> 00:02:09.279
own language for the graphs.

00:02:09.279 --> 00:02:10.720
It's something you have to learn.

00:02:10.720 --> 00:02:16.479
It's much different from ggplot2's language, but it gives you a lot of flexibility.

00:02:16.479 --> 00:02:23.440
You can also just convert any ggplot2 graphic to Plotly automatically if you like the way

00:02:23.440 --> 00:02:25.320
ggplot2 laid out things.

00:02:25.320 --> 00:02:29.759
But if you want to add things sort of trace by trace, you might want to do what I did

00:02:29.759 --> 00:02:33.940
was go most straightly to Plotly.

00:02:33.940 --> 00:02:38.960
So there's some new Plotly graphics functions I've been adding to my existing packages over

00:02:38.960 --> 00:02:45.279
the last couple of years and I've been adding a lot of HTML methods as I get more away from

00:02:45.279 --> 00:02:48.119
LaTeX and PDF into HTML.

00:02:48.119 --> 00:02:53.960
I've added a whole lot of functions for creating customized HTML output that you can include

00:02:53.960 --> 00:02:56.360
right in your reports.

00:02:56.360 --> 00:03:02.520
And there's special HTML methods for the describe function and the summaryM function.

00:03:02.520 --> 00:03:09.080
SummaryM is like for creating table one in a clinical trial report.

00:03:09.080 --> 00:03:14.360
HisboxP is for making spike histograms with extra information added to them.

00:03:14.440 --> 00:03:17.639
PlotP is for making interactive survival plots.

00:03:17.639 --> 00:03:25.960
And then there's advanced HTML table makers using the HTML table package in R.

00:03:25.960 --> 00:03:28.279
So let's get to clinical trial reports.

00:03:28.279 --> 00:03:33.479
So the applications I'm talking about are where you're doing, say, a randomized clinical

00:03:33.479 --> 00:03:39.559
trial to study a treatment versus some control, or you might be doing a drug study, something

00:03:39.559 --> 00:03:41.759
in the pharmaceutical industry.

00:03:41.759 --> 00:03:43.839
And there's two types of clinical trial reports.

00:03:43.839 --> 00:03:48.399
There's sort of final clinical trial reports and there's interim reports as often used

00:03:48.399 --> 00:03:54.000
in monitoring the conduct of a clinical trial that you might give to a data monitoring committee,

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:59.000
also called a data and safety monitoring board.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:07.399
And so the task that I started with was developing high-level abstractions for the job of creating

00:04:07.399 --> 00:04:08.399
reports.

00:04:08.399 --> 00:04:12.399
Most statisticians, when they create a big report, they sort of start over.

00:04:12.399 --> 00:04:17.160
They may have some code they used from previous trials, but they do a lot of new coding and

00:04:17.160 --> 00:04:19.399
it's quite repetitive.

00:04:19.399 --> 00:04:24.839
So if you can make high-level abstractions, I think you can foster better statistical

00:04:24.839 --> 00:04:31.959
analysis and better reporting practices and make everything reproducible and really minimize

00:04:31.959 --> 00:04:33.600
programming.

00:04:33.760 --> 00:04:41.920
And the authors of reports about human subjects' research get really tired of reading through

00:04:41.920 --> 00:04:46.119
tables and they usually fall asleep, they don't pay attention to things, and tables

00:04:46.119 --> 00:04:49.839
are not that good for showing patterns anyway.

00:04:49.839 --> 00:04:52.839
And so we really want to get rid of that.

00:04:52.839 --> 00:04:56.320
Now there's many standard components to clinical trial reports.

00:04:56.320 --> 00:05:03.160
These are some of them, a summary of how you were able to accrue subjects into the study,

00:05:03.160 --> 00:05:09.399
how did the patient flow occur and what sort of exclusions did you find between the accrual

00:05:09.399 --> 00:05:16.679
or the screening of subjects before you randomized them to experimental treatment, describing

00:05:16.679 --> 00:05:25.200
baseline variables, longitudinal analysis, adverse event analysis, lab safety parameters,

00:05:25.200 --> 00:05:31.920
event timing and incidence, and sequential monitoring of event probabilities.

00:05:31.920 --> 00:05:37.880
So the philosophy is that tables really do not lead to pattern recognition and graphics

00:05:37.880 --> 00:05:39.200
are better.

00:05:39.200 --> 00:05:43.160
If you have more than two numbers, I think a graph is better than a table.

00:05:43.160 --> 00:05:45.640
In other words, graph is almost always better.

00:05:45.640 --> 00:05:49.839
And graphs should use features that humans are really good at perceiving, such as position

00:05:49.839 --> 00:05:52.200
along a common scale.

00:05:52.200 --> 00:05:54.399
And then we need side posts on the graphics.

00:05:54.399 --> 00:05:58.519
So when I'm reading a long report, I lose track of where I am in terms of, say, which

00:05:58.519 --> 00:06:01.480
subjects are currently being displayed or analyzed.

00:06:01.480 --> 00:06:03.720
And I'll show you what that means.

00:06:03.720 --> 00:06:04.720
Tables are secondary.

00:06:04.720 --> 00:06:07.200
They can be in an appendix or hyperlinked.

00:06:07.200 --> 00:06:14.600
Or what's better, I think, is to have pieces of tables as hover text from a plot.

00:06:14.600 --> 00:06:18.480
And then this was probably a little more controversial.

00:06:18.480 --> 00:06:25.359
Most studies where you're doing an A-B comparison, the way an A-B comparison is really created

00:06:25.359 --> 00:06:30.279
is that confidence intervals for A are not relevant to the design and confidence intervals

00:06:30.279 --> 00:06:32.160
for B are not relevant to the design.

00:06:32.160 --> 00:06:36.239
They're actually inconsistent with a parallel group design.

00:06:36.239 --> 00:06:40.000
But the design is made to give confidence intervals for differences between A and B.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:42.399
And that's what we want to emphasize.

00:06:42.399 --> 00:06:47.799
We want to show the entire distribution when possible, favor quantiles over means and standard

00:06:47.799 --> 00:06:52.640
deviations, and then I personally don't like percentages and I do everything I can to get

00:06:52.640 --> 00:06:55.359
rid of percentages.

00:06:55.359 --> 00:06:57.200
That's a personal opinion.

00:06:57.200 --> 00:07:02.880
So I have an older package that used the LaTeX and PDF model, and this is a very, very stable

00:07:02.880 --> 00:07:03.880
package.

00:07:03.880 --> 00:07:09.480
It's been around for many years, used in production in some really huge multinational clinical

00:07:09.480 --> 00:07:10.480
trials.

00:07:10.480 --> 00:07:15.679
And then the newer package, which is not on CRAN yet, which is hReport for HTML report.

00:07:15.679 --> 00:07:21.119
So in these packages, there's lots of utility functions, high-level report components, unified

00:07:21.119 --> 00:07:23.359
handling of figure generation and caption.

00:07:23.359 --> 00:07:28.359
So when you write a long report, you spend a lot of time writing figure captions.

00:07:28.359 --> 00:07:32.880
So the figure captions are all automatically generated by these packages.

00:07:32.880 --> 00:07:35.399
And then there's some new graphical elements.

00:07:35.399 --> 00:07:43.640
So the high-level functions are accrual report, exclusion report, descriptive statistics,

00:07:43.640 --> 00:07:49.119
event report, and serve report for time to event analysis.

00:07:49.119 --> 00:07:53.480
Now when you're writing a package and you want to implement things at a high level,

00:07:53.480 --> 00:07:57.959
you really have to survey best practices, and it's your opportunity to implement best

00:07:57.959 --> 00:08:03.119
practices and also to create best practices if people like the package.

00:08:03.119 --> 00:08:08.000
And so instead of doing one-off reports, if you start saying, what should be in a patient

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:14.839
screening report or accrual report, and really nailing that, and then making it so that people

00:08:14.839 --> 00:08:19.359
can join the project on GitHub and they can extend the report with new options or change

00:08:19.359 --> 00:08:26.200
the format, it's much better than just coding from scratch for each report.

00:08:26.200 --> 00:08:31.000
Number at risk report, and in the future, there'll be a sequential monitoring boundary

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:32.719
sort of report.

00:08:32.719 --> 00:08:37.280
And the format of all these functions, the way you call them, is using the formula language.

00:08:37.280 --> 00:08:42.719
You have your analysis variables on the left-hand side of the model, separated by plus, and

00:08:42.719 --> 00:08:47.200
then you have your stratification variables and optional ID variable if you're analyzing

00:08:47.200 --> 00:08:51.880
something where there's multiple records per subject.

00:08:51.880 --> 00:08:56.840
So R Markdown creates HTML documents, and these allow semi-interactive graphics.

00:08:56.840 --> 00:09:04.359
So if you're using Plotly, this uses HTML widgets, and those are included in your HTML

00:09:04.359 --> 00:09:09.400
without you doing anything special whatsoever, and they'll display beautifully on virtually

00:09:09.479 --> 00:09:14.799
any browser, and they'll automatically resize for viewing on a tablet, and it's very effective

00:09:14.799 --> 00:09:17.239
to view these reports on a tablet.

00:09:17.239 --> 00:09:19.200
And then our functions write HTML.

00:09:19.200 --> 00:09:26.039
They write regular tabular output, hyperlinks, navigation bars, and almost no tables.

00:09:26.039 --> 00:09:31.599
And then hovering over a part of a graphic will display the relevant portion of the table.

00:09:31.599 --> 00:09:37.960
So I don't display whole tables anymore, but just portions of tables on demand.

00:09:37.960 --> 00:09:44.000
So now we get into the two examples, and then if you download the slides, you can click

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:49.039
on these links to see them in much more detail.

00:09:49.039 --> 00:10:05.039
The first thing you notice is we have a new table of contents function in the HMIS package

00:10:05.080 --> 00:10:09.119
that it doesn't waste so much space on the left with your floating table of contents,

00:10:09.119 --> 00:10:12.000
and then it allows you to specify the level.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:15.960
So if you click on three, you'll get a three-level outline, and if you click on two,

00:10:15.960 --> 00:10:20.880
you just get a two-level outline, and one is a one-level, but the most important thing is

00:10:20.880 --> 00:10:25.640
to be able to get rid of the outline altogether.

00:10:25.640 --> 00:10:31.960
And so the other thing that we have in this, you see that little L?

00:10:31.960 --> 00:10:39.400
That's a little figure icon for a graph, so that means this is a figure,

00:10:39.400 --> 00:10:43.960
and this is a short figure caption, and clicking there will go to that figure.

00:10:45.960 --> 00:10:51.320
This has a bunch of philosophy stuff, and then notes about figure captions,

00:10:51.320 --> 00:10:55.679
and these are the signposts that are used in each graph.

00:10:55.679 --> 00:11:03.640
And so to keep me aware of where I am in a report, I have these signposts below each graph.

00:11:03.640 --> 00:11:10.359
So what that means is you have a little bar here where the red is telling you how many

00:11:10.359 --> 00:11:14.919
of the enrolled subjects are included in the current analysis being displayed.

00:11:14.919 --> 00:11:17.400
So if you saw a bar like that that's full height,

00:11:17.400 --> 00:11:20.719
that would mean you're analyzing all the enrolled subjects.

00:11:20.719 --> 00:11:25.119
This would mean you're analyzing three-quarters of the enrolled subjects,

00:11:25.119 --> 00:11:27.440
but all of the randomized subjects.

00:11:27.440 --> 00:11:32.880
This would show that you're analyzing one-fourth of the enrolled subjects,

00:11:32.880 --> 00:11:35.520
and only one-half of the randomized subjects.

00:11:35.520 --> 00:11:39.640
So the green is the proportion of randomized subjects you're currently analyzing,

00:11:39.640 --> 00:11:42.760
and then if it's stratified for treatment, you'll get two more,

00:11:42.760 --> 00:11:46.000
and the last two bars will tell you what proportion of those randomized

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:49.400
to one treatment are currently being considered in the analysis,

00:11:49.400 --> 00:11:54.799
what proportion of randomized to another treatment B are being considered.

00:11:54.799 --> 00:12:01.200
And then this is the first output, and you can click on code to see the code for any of these.

00:12:01.200 --> 00:12:02.840
This is the accrual report.

00:12:02.840 --> 00:12:06.760
So this actually took one of the longest times to write,

00:12:06.760 --> 00:12:09.880
because when you have a multi-site clinical trial,

00:12:09.880 --> 00:12:12.919
that may also be a multinational clinical trial.

00:12:12.919 --> 00:12:18.000
You have countries, regions, sites, so it's a very hierarchical organization.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:23.440
And to really summarize a multi-site, multinational trial the way that you need to,

00:12:23.440 --> 00:12:27.200
took a little bit of thought, but this is a trial snapshot.

00:12:27.200 --> 00:12:32.880
So you get your overall summaries about the trial content,

00:12:32.880 --> 00:12:36.080
and how many people are passing the screening stage.

00:12:36.080 --> 00:12:41.559
Then you get your accrual, and this is where Plotly comes in, because you can just hover

00:12:41.559 --> 00:12:46.080
and see your target numbers of patients you should have accrued by that time,

00:12:46.080 --> 00:13:01.239
versus the actual number that you've accrued by that time, and you see that's May 1994.

00:13:01.239 --> 00:13:06.520
There is the little signpost over here, which you can barely see probably from where you are,

00:13:06.520 --> 00:13:11.719
and there's some fine details showing you the number of non-missing observations analyzed

00:13:11.719 --> 00:13:13.039
and the groups being analyzed.

00:13:13.039 --> 00:13:16.919
You can just zoom in on that to see detailed denominators.

00:13:16.919 --> 00:13:20.640
This is just a dot chart showing the number of sites,

00:13:20.640 --> 00:13:24.840
how many subjects were randomized at how many sites.

00:13:24.840 --> 00:13:35.840
So looking at the randomization frequency over sites, and then we have another graph like that.

00:13:35.840 --> 00:13:40.719
Then we start getting to baseline variables, and this is where we start using the features

00:13:40.719 --> 00:13:43.320
of Plotly more effectively.

00:13:43.320 --> 00:13:50.400
So this is just showing the proportion of females in treatment A and in treatment B,

00:13:50.400 --> 00:13:55.000
and you see on the right the legend shows you the color code for treatment A and B,

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:59.080
which is used throughout the report, and then if you hover over that,

00:13:59.080 --> 00:14:07.119
you'll see that this is .222 of the subjects were female in treatment A,

00:14:07.119 --> 00:14:13.559
and this was for all regions, and you can see the numerator 18 and the denominator is 81.

00:14:13.559 --> 00:14:18.400
So one thing I learned early on in this is you always give numerators to denominators

00:14:18.400 --> 00:14:20.159
because somebody's going to ask you.

00:14:20.159 --> 00:14:22.960
You don't want to leave it to guesswork.

00:14:22.960 --> 00:14:28.239
The other element of this graph, and of course you can turn things off by clicking here.

00:14:28.239 --> 00:14:32.679
So if I didn't want to show the stratified data by region, I can just click on the right,

00:14:32.679 --> 00:14:34.440
and that will turn those traces off.

00:14:34.479 --> 00:14:38.520
That's just a nice feature of Plotly, which we'll see more in a minute,

00:14:38.520 --> 00:14:44.000
but the other design consideration here is when you're showing the proportion randomized to A

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:48.119
and proportion randomized to B who smoke, which is these two dots down here,

00:14:48.119 --> 00:14:55.840
you also see it stratified by region, and you can see that this is north, the north region here.

00:14:55.840 --> 00:15:03.559
So I think of the stratification by region as something that's subservient to the main stratification.

00:15:03.559 --> 00:15:08.280
So the main stratification is treatment A versus B, and if I want to further stratify

00:15:08.280 --> 00:15:13.000
by region, those dots are below the main dots, and they're smaller.

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:19.799
So to denote that those are subservient or minor stratification, I'm using a smaller size,

00:15:19.799 --> 00:15:23.200
and if you click on the legend, you can turn those off.

00:15:23.200 --> 00:15:28.960
Now this is the way I've settled as my favorite way to display continuous data is really you need

00:15:28.960 --> 00:15:35.799
to show the data, and box plots don't really have a good inked information ratio.

00:15:35.799 --> 00:15:37.400
They just don't show enough.

00:15:37.400 --> 00:15:40.280
A box plot will not show by modality.

00:15:40.280 --> 00:15:44.719
It'll completely hide it, but a histogram will show by modality.

00:15:44.719 --> 00:15:50.320
If you have digit preference in your data, more numbers entering in five or zero,

00:15:50.320 --> 00:15:54.559
you'll see digit preference very clearly, and so I found the secret formula

00:15:54.559 --> 00:15:56.599
for how many bins there should be in a histogram.

00:15:56.599 --> 00:16:02.640
It's either 100 or 200, independent of the sample size, but if you have fewer

00:16:02.640 --> 00:16:07.719
than 100 distinct values in your data, you would use that fewer number as the number of bins,

00:16:07.719 --> 00:16:13.080
but you essentially have one bin per possible value up to about 200 bins,

00:16:13.080 --> 00:16:17.799
and that way you have all the resolution you need, and it scales to huge data sets,

00:16:17.799 --> 00:16:22.119
but in addition to showing the histogram, which has a lot of information,

00:16:22.119 --> 00:16:25.440
you can show the elements of the box plot plus more.

00:16:25.440 --> 00:16:30.919
So you can see that below each histogram, you see the mean is with a dot,

00:16:30.919 --> 00:16:34.679
the median is with a big vertical bar, and then you see the quartiles

00:16:34.679 --> 00:16:37.679
in the .05 and .95 quantiles.

00:16:37.679 --> 00:16:40.580
So you see all the box plot information plus more,

00:16:40.580 --> 00:16:43.000
but the histograms are more informative, and then if you wanted

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:53.520
to turn off the box plot stuff, you just click here, and that's no longer there.

00:16:53.520 --> 00:16:56.039
So you can easily turn that off.

00:16:56.039 --> 00:16:58.799
So that's how I display continuous data.

00:16:58.799 --> 00:17:00.280
That's stratified by treatment.

00:17:00.280 --> 00:17:05.359
You see this for a bunch of variables, and you'll see on all these displays,

00:17:05.359 --> 00:17:10.640
like here in the fine print, you'll see denominators for each variable being displayed.

00:17:10.640 --> 00:17:13.319
That's a number of non-missing values.

00:17:13.319 --> 00:17:16.239
Then there's various displays for longitudinal data.

00:17:16.239 --> 00:17:19.920
This is for longitudinal binary data, like adverse events.

00:17:19.920 --> 00:17:21.640
I display that lots of different ways,

00:17:21.640 --> 00:17:25.319
and then for just showing overall incidents of adverse events,

00:17:25.319 --> 00:17:30.959
I just use a dot chart where each dot, you're showing the proportion that have that event,

00:17:30.959 --> 00:17:35.239
and if you hover over it, you'll see this is diarrhea treatment B,

00:17:35.239 --> 00:17:39.760
20 out of 169 subjects had that event.

00:17:39.760 --> 00:17:45.400
But then you have a confidence band for the difference, and if you position that at the midpoint

00:17:45.400 --> 00:17:49.180
of the two, and it's the half of the width of the confidence interval,

00:17:49.180 --> 00:17:52.540
that has the property that it touches those two dots if and only

00:17:52.540 --> 00:17:55.619
if there's no significant difference at that alpha level

00:17:55.619 --> 00:17:58.020
that you're using for the confidence interval.

00:17:58.020 --> 00:18:12.180
And then if you hover over the bars, you will see, no, I can't get that to pop up right now.

00:18:12.180 --> 00:18:15.380
You're supposed to see the actual confidence intervals for the difference,

00:18:15.380 --> 00:18:19.780
and you can turn those confidence intervals off if you want by clicking on the right.

00:18:19.780 --> 00:18:27.739
Lots of ways to display longitudinal data, and then I want to show you just one item

00:18:27.739 --> 00:18:35.579
from the other report, this is the exclusion report.

00:18:35.579 --> 00:18:38.859
And so it analyzes what is causing patients to be excluded,

00:18:38.859 --> 00:18:41.739
and it doesn't ask you what order to analyze those in.

00:18:41.739 --> 00:18:47.459
It finds the major exclusion, which would be here, no significant coronary artery disease,

00:18:47.459 --> 00:18:50.579
that excluded 11 subjects from the trial.

00:18:50.579 --> 00:18:56.979
And then what excluded the next largest number of subjects was pneumonia within six weeks.

00:18:56.979 --> 00:19:01.459
And then for each exclusion, it reports the incremental exclusion,

00:19:01.459 --> 00:19:05.739
so how many new subjects are excluded because of pneumonia

00:19:05.739 --> 00:19:09.699
after you've already excluded those without CAD.

00:19:09.699 --> 00:19:13.900
And it shows the marginal exclusions, how many people will be excluded because of pneumonia,

00:19:13.900 --> 00:19:17.219
whether or not they were excluded for anything else.

00:19:17.219 --> 00:19:23.819
And then in terms of survival report, this is the kind of output you get.

00:19:23.819 --> 00:19:27.979
And what I really like about it, besides having a confidence interval for the difference

00:19:27.979 --> 00:19:31.420
of two Kaplan-Meier curves, or this is one minus this,

00:19:31.420 --> 00:19:35.619
so this is cumulative incidence curves, is it recognizes that the number

00:19:35.619 --> 00:19:37.619
at risk is really a continuous variable.

00:19:37.619 --> 00:19:40.780
So I don't want to just show the number at risk at yearly intervals.

00:19:40.780 --> 00:19:44.219
I want to show that as a continuous function of the follow-up time.

00:19:44.219 --> 00:19:49.979
So as you hover over these different areas, you will, you'll see that,

00:19:49.979 --> 00:19:53.099
you'll see the number at risk at exactly that time point.

00:19:53.099 --> 00:19:58.540
It's just another way where I think you can use Plotly very effectively.

00:19:58.540 --> 00:20:03.579
So if you get the slides and go into those clicks, you'll see those,

00:20:03.579 --> 00:20:08.020
and more information can be attained at these three sites.

00:20:08.020 --> 00:20:10.020
So thank you very much for listening.

00:20:10.020 --> 00:20:27.300
We have a few questions, we have a few minutes.

00:20:27.300 --> 00:20:32.060
So one of the more popular questions, is there a function to make consort diagrams

00:20:32.060 --> 00:20:36.140
or can you do alluvial plots for patient flows?

00:20:36.140 --> 00:20:38.739
That was asked, might have been the person asking it now.

00:20:38.739 --> 00:20:42.020
I asked that on Twitter the other day, and somebody responded to use one

00:20:42.020 --> 00:20:47.540
of the general figure drawing packages in R, like, I think, I don't know,

00:20:47.540 --> 00:20:50.219
it's TICC-Z or one that uses GraphVis.

00:20:50.219 --> 00:20:54.339
But I don't think anybody's packaged those sort of things into a ready-to-use function.

00:20:54.339 --> 00:20:59.180
I think it would be nice.

00:20:59.180 --> 00:21:01.540
Maybe we'll do one more question.

00:21:01.540 --> 00:21:05.459
How can a staff statistician working in clinical trials, do you think,

00:21:05.459 --> 00:21:13.339
convince PIs that it's worth it to switch over to HTML reports from Word or PDF?

00:21:13.339 --> 00:21:16.579
It'll depend on the age of the person on the committee.

00:21:16.579 --> 00:21:21.180
So I found that every committee has one person that's as old as I am,

00:21:21.180 --> 00:21:23.979
and they want to see paper, not just PDF.

00:21:23.979 --> 00:21:26.020
They actually want to print the darn thing.

00:21:26.020 --> 00:21:28.459
And that's kind of a lost cause.

00:21:28.500 --> 00:21:32.500
So I would stick to the younger committee members, giving them state-of-the-art,

00:21:32.500 --> 00:21:35.540
and then letting them embarrass the older committee member.

00:21:35.540 --> 00:21:43.540
I'm a big fan of HTML output, so I appreciate that answer, Frank.

00:21:43.540 --> 00:21:45.020
Thank you guys all for attending.

00:21:45.020 --> 00:21:46.300
That's the end of this session.

00:21:46.300 --> 00:21:49.900
Give a round of applause to all of our speakers.

00:21:58.459 --> 00:21:59.459
Thank you.

00:21:59.459 --> 00:22:00.459
Have a great day.

00:22:00.459 --> 00:22:01.459
Thanks.

00:22:01.459 --> 00:22:02.459
Bye.

00:22:02.459 --> 00:22:02.459


